The community wetland users largely belong to scheduled tribes, scheduled castes, (for more information, see MTA, 1956) and Muslim minority populations, and have high livelihood dependencies and long-standing associations with the wetlands for aquaculture, agriculture, and horticulture purposes. Wetlands managed by private users involve a large proportion from the general caste population along with scheduled tribes and scheduled castes. The labor work in private wetlands is done mostly by part-time migrant laborers, along with a few full-time workers (Table 1
                        ). All interviewed stakeholders from both types of wetlands produce a variety of freshwater fish along with seasonal vegetables (Table 2
                        ).

The perceived importance of the ecosystem service provisioning functions of the EKW was high among community users (Fig. 3
                        ). The respondents from the community-managed wetlands readily recognized their dependency on the EKW for daily consumption, collection of fodder for livestock, firewood, and timber wood, whereas the private wetland users were not dependent on the wetlands for any of these purposes (Fig. 4
                        ). Medicinal plants were valued highly by most community wetland users (96 % of respondents), but few of the private wetland users (8 %).
                           “We eat what we grow and we grow more than enough. Even after selling at a profitable rate to the local market, we can feed all members of our bheri everyday… Working in the bheri requires physical labor, and small accidents or insect bites are inevitable, but we always have elders around us to take care of our medical needs with the help of these local plants… Many people from the city raised a lot of questions about the quality of our harvests because it’s from wastewater treatment bodies. We tell them that if they would survey us about how frequently we fall ill or have chronic or fatal illnesses, then they will get an answer. We have a diverse range of food, depending on the season, but we get all our nutritional needs taken care of well.” (Community wetland user, male, 67 years).
                           “Oh! Why spend money to buy vegetables and fruits from the outside market when our soil is so fertile it can grow everything? What does a human need to eat for a healthy living? Rice, fish curry, dal (lentils), a vegetable curry, and some wild greens like spinach, amaranthus, or goosefoots (Chenopodium) or water spinach (Ipomoea aquatica), etc., depending on the season. Once a week we have meat and egg, which are easily available from our backyards. We have all types of fruit trees common to Kolkata; in between work in the evening we pluck whichever fruits we want as a snack. We work hard all day, we eat freshly grown food, to me that’s all we need for being healthy.” (Community wetland user, male, 42 years).

Based on the open-ended questions in the questionnaire, the main perceived threats to wetland degradation among both community and private users were identified as lack of ownership rights, siltation, urbanization, land-use change, land encroachment by real estate, and discharge of unwanted waste materials or chemical contamination. Lack of manpower due to emigration, irregular maintenance, other encroachment threats from aspects such as local power politics, long distance from main sewage canals, transformation of wetlands to agricultural or paddy fields, and depletion of wild edible flowers and greens were also among the top identified threats (Figs. 5
                         and 6
                        ). The users of privately managed wetlands identified major threats from land ownership issues and real estate and other encroachment threats, while the community users found siltation, lack of manpower due to emigration, lack of proximity to the main sewage canal, land-use change, transformation of wetlands to agricultural or paddy lands, and depletion of wild edible flowers and greens to be the major concerns for the depletion of the wetlands. Both expressed a similar intensity of concern for the discharge of unwanted waste materials, such as chemical contamination from nearby tanneries and rapid urban development. The three interlinked challenges that were discussed by the cooperative wetland members were rapid urban development, land use change around wetlands, and depletion of edible wildflowers and greens (biodiversity). According to them, this is another major threat to the health of the wetlands which is beyond their control. They said, “You see the kind of urban development happening around? Wherever you look around, you will see high-rise buildings and apartments, roads, and gated colonies. These buildings don’t come up in a day, there is continuous construction work going on all throughout the year, which brings more silt and degrades the pond porosity and channels with other wetlands. It is choking the fish ponds eventually. This also affects the vegetation quality in the embankments. Usually, the soil in the embankments is basically silts removed from the ponds; the soil is heavily fertile, and we do not need any added fertilizers – but we can see the changes in the sizes, colors, amount, and shapes.” (Community wetland user, male, 45 years). Another respondent added, “While cleaning the weeds, we have noticed that some wild plants like bakhra are not growing anymore. The flowers of these plants attracted a lot of pollinators. We also used to sell them locally – you can eat them, they are very good for vision, and taste like pumpkin flowers. We don’t really see them anymore.” (Community wetland user, female, 38 years). The conversation in the cooperative wetlands further adds, “Earlier, in between the wetlands periphery and the city, were the habitats of cattle grazers. A huge community of cattle grazers lived there and reared their cattle in the green open spaces, or ‘math’. The urine and fecal excretory matter of these cattle were used to mix with the wastewater which was gold for our aquaculture, vegetation, and agriculture. All these settlers were moved out from parts of the city as the urban development boomed in. These grazers have now moved to the other side of the wetlands, far away from the city. Unfortunately, the wastewater comes from the city to the wetlands, we can’t take it from the other side. This impacted our livelihoods to a huge extent. We never had to think of any form of fertilizers or added food for fish.” (Community wetland user, male, 71 years).
